## What this slice does
Stamps attributes.integration on the callback/tracer family — integrations that
build an attributes dict and call client.create_call directly (not via weave.op):
- langchain: apply_integration_metadata(call_attrs, LANGCHAIN_INTEGRATION) before
  create_call. call_attrs is the call_attributes context dict, so setdefault-style
  merge preserves any user-set integration.
- llamaindex: span_attributes/event_attributes seeded from
  LLAMAINDEX_INTEGRATION.as_attributes() (then weave.kind added if present).
- claude_agent_sdk (legacy calls): spread ...CLAUDE_AGENT_SDK_INTEGRATION
  .as_attributes() into each create_call's attributes={"kind": ...} (5 sites).
- openai_agents (direct create_call path), verdict (1 site): spread into the dict.
- gepa_callback: _kind_attrs() now includes the integration block; the 4 attribute-
  less create_calls get attributes=GEPA_INTEGRATION.as_attributes().
- dspy_callback (3 sites), openai_realtime/state_exporter (9 sites): added
  attributes=<INTEGRATION>.as_attributes() to each create_call.

## Key decisions
- Used setdefault/spread so a user-set "integration" key isn't clobbered (mirrors
  the op-level lowest-precedence intent). Collisions are not realistic but kept
  predictable.
- distribution_name: langchain->langchain-core, llamaindex->llama-index-core,
  openai_agents->openai-agents, openai_realtime->openai. Others default to name.
- claude_agent_sdk keeps its pre-existing top-level "kind" attribute convention
  (not nested under "weave"); I did not change that — only added integration.

## How it was built
openai_realtime (9 varied create_call sites) was delegated to a subagent with a
strict rule; the rest done directly. All edited modules import cleanly.

## Testing
The create_call-carries-integration path is covered by
tests/trace/test_integration_metadata.py::test_create_call_carries_integration_attributes
(slice 1). langchain/llamaindex/etc. integration tests need their libs (not in the
base env) so weren't run here; the modules import fine and the mechanism is proven.
ruff clean.

## Depends on
Slice 1 (integration_metadata). openai_agents.py here defines OPENAI_AGENTS_INTEGRATION
which slice 4's otel_processor reuses — keep slice 3 below slice 4.

## Test coverage added (follow-up: "callbacks integrations need tests too")

The original commit stamped 8 callback/tracer integrations but added no tests.
Added shape-confirming attributes["integration"] asserts (name / truthy version /
meta.package_name) to the 6 purely-callback integrations:

- langchain (langchain-core), llamaindex (llama-index-core), openai_agents
  (openai-agents), verdict (verdict), claude_agent_sdk (claude_agent_sdk):
  robust style in each one's existing call test — filter fetched calls to
  name==<vendor> first, because these agent/tracer traces ALSO contain
  sub-integration calls (e.g. openai) that carry their own integration block.
- openai_realtime (openai): test_state_exporter.py drives a DummyWeaveClient fake
  whose create_call() discarded the attributes kwarg, so the stamped block was not
  observable. Enhanced the fake to record what create_call receives
  (self.created_attributes) and asserted the block in
  test_response_without_conversation_id_has_no_thread_id. VERIFIED locally - passes.

dspy and gepa also have callback paths (dspy_callback.py, gepa_callback.py) but
stamp the SAME name ("dspy"/"gepa") as their op-based counterparts, so the
name-based asserts added in the op-based commit (dspy_test.py / gepa_test.py)
already cover them; not duplicated here.

